'''Yamahata Kofun Group''' (山畑古墳群, ''Yamahata Kofun-gun'') is a {{ill|Clustered Kofun|ja|群集墳|1=Gunshufun|qq=draft|qq=draft}} located in the southeastern part of {{ill|Higashiōsaka, Osaka|ja|東大阪市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Japan (around Kamishijō-chō and Hyōtan-yama-chō). It is the largest kofun cluster in Higashiōsaka City.

== Overview ==

The kofun were built from the late {{ill|6th century|ja|6世紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to the early {{ill|7th century|ja|7世紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Most of them are small circular tombs ({{ill|Empun (Round Kofun)|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) with diameters of 10–15 meters, but there are also twin circular tombs and unique types like a top-round, bottom-square tomb ({{ill|Jōen Kahōfun|ja|上円下方墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). 

Originally, over 100 tumuli were believed to exist, but due to urban development, about 70 have been confirmed. Most are concentrated around the {{ill|Higashiōsaka City Folk Museum|ja|東大阪市立郷土博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The kofun typically feature corridor-style stone chambers ({{ill|Yokoana-shiki Sekishitsu|ja|横穴石室|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), and numerous burial goods related to horse gear have been excavated.

The surrounding area is thought to have been a settlement of an immigrant clan ({{ill|Toraijin|ja|渡来人|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) who managed horse breeding and cavalry ({{ill|Umakaibe|ja|馬飼部|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), leading to the nickname "Village of Horse Breeders." The kofun are believed to be the burial sites of this influential group.

== Major Kofun ==

=== Yamahata No. 22 Kofun ===
Located within the grounds of the {{ill|Higashiōsaka City Folk Museum|ja|東大阪市立郷土博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it was originally a twin circular kofun ({{ill|Sōenfun|ja|双円墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) with eastern and western mounds. However, the eastern mound has been destroyed. The remaining western mound has a diameter of 15 meters and a height of approximately 4.5 meters, with a preserved stone chamber. Excavations have yielded earthenware, accessories, and horse fittings, which are housed and displayed in the museum.
* {{Coord|34|39|38|N|135|39|04|E|map_size:20000}}
* The museum grounds also contain Nos. 38, 39, 40, and 41 kofun, but their mounds have been lost, leaving only exposed or completely destroyed stone chambers.

=== Yamahata No. 51 Kofun ===
Also known as "Nariyama Kofun," it is a circular mound with a diameter of approximately 15 meters and a height of 3 meters. The burial chamber is not currently open.
* {{Coord|34|39|40|N|135|38|38.5|E|map_size:20000}}

=== Yamahata No. 52 Kofun ===
The lowest-altitude kofun in the Yamahata Kofun Group, estimated to be a twin circular mound from the late {{ill|6th century|ja|6世紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, with a total length of about 50 meters. Due to its type, it is commonly called "'''Hyōtan-yama'''" ("Gourd Mountain"). The northern mound is referred to as "Ōtsuka" (Great Mound), while the southern mound is called "Onizuka" (Demon Mound).
* Located near {{ill|Hyōtan-yama Inari Shrine|ja|瓢箪山稲荷神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, where foxes were once kept inside the stone chamber of the northern mound (Ōtsuka).
* {{Coord|34|39|39|N|135|38|32|E|map_size:20000}}

